  user_input {
    user_response: "Build me an app with screens that look like this. You can hotlink images from the HTML\n\nThis architecture specification bridges the gap between design (Google Stitch) and intelligence (Google AI Studio) to build a state-of-the-art, highly localized Japan Disaster Response Command Center.\n\nSystem Blueprint\nOur system splits responsibilities into two optimized environments:\n\n  +-----------------------------------------------------------------+\n  |                    FRONTEND (Google Stitch)                     |\n  |                                                                 |\n  |  +--------------------+  +------------------+  +-------------+  |\n  |  |  NERV Dark Dashboard |  | Interactive Map  |  | Agent Feed  |  |\n  |  +--------------------+  +------------------+  +-------------+  |\n  +--------------------------------+--------------------------------+\n                                   | REST / SSE (Server-Sent Events)\n                                   v\n  +-----------------------------------------------------------------+\n  |                    BACKEND (FastAPI / Node)                     |\n  |                                                                 |\n  |  +--------------------+  +------------------+  +-------------+  |\n  |  | Spatial Math Engine|  | MCP Gateway      |  | Local APIs  |  |\n  |  | (Deterministic)    |  | (Twitter/JMA)    |  | (P2PQuake)  |  |\n  |  +--------------------+  +------------------+  +-------------+  |\n  +--------------------------------+--------------------------------+\n                                   | JSON / Function Calling\n                                   v\n  +-----------------------------------------------------------------+\n  |                  INTELLIGENCE (Google AI Studio)                |\n  |                                                                 |\n  |            Gemini 2.0 Flash (Multimodal & Agent Control)        |\n  +-----------------------------------------------------------------+\n1. UI Engineering Spec (Google Stitch)\nGoogle Stitch is our rapid UI prototyping engine. It will generate our high-fidelity frontend (React + Tailwind CSS) styled in a dark-theme, high-visibility layout inspired by Gehirn\'s NERV app.\n\nA. Stitch Prompt (Copy-Paste to Google Stitch Canvas)\nPaste this text prompt into your Stitch visual canvas workspace to generate the layout:\n\nCreate a high-fidelity React dashboard using Tailwind CSS. \nThe theme must be inspired by Special Agency NERV Disaster Prevention App:\n- Background: Pitch black (#050505) and dark charcoal (#121212)\n- Accents: Neon Orange (#FF6600) for warnings, Neon Purple (#9D00FF) for critical alerts, and Toxic green (#00FF66) for stable systems.\n- Font: Monospaced, tech-operational feel.\n\nLayout Requirements:\n1. Header: Shows \"NERV GEOSPATIAL COMMAND CENTER\" in bold orange, with a ticking clock, location selector (Default: Tokyo), and a glowing green \"SYSTEM ONLINE\" indicator.\n2. Center-Left (Live Map Container): A map window styled with dark vectors (to be populated by Google Maps / GSI Tiles) showing local escape routes, evacuation sites, and seismic epicenters.\n3. Center-Right (Real-time Intel Stream): A scrolling log of incoming news feeds and automated tweets with raw text and images.\n4. Bottom-Left (Shelter & Resource Locator): A grid panel showing the closest designated shelters (\346\214\207\345\256\232\351\201\277\351\233\243\346\211\200) from a user\'s geolocation, complete with distance indicators and hazard compatibility badges (Earthquake, Tsunami, Flood safety flags).\n5. Bottom-Right (Gemini 2.0 Flash Multi-Agent Output): A split panel showing:\n   - \"Triage Engine\" status log.\n   - \"Resource Coordinator\" recommended actions.\n   - \"Public Broadcaster\" dynamic multi-lingual alerts ready to copy.\n6. Controls: Simulated controls to upload a satellite photo or trigger a mock seismic event (e.g., Magnitude 7.2 earthquake off Tokyo Bay).\nB. Generated Component Architecture (Exported from Stitch)\nDashboardLayout.tsx: Grid wrapper managing the 3-column layout.\nMapCanvas.tsx: Hosts the dark-styled interactive Google Maps API.\nShelterGrid.tsx: Lists closest locations filtered by distance and status.\nAgentResponseCard.tsx: Standard component handling streaming output using Tailwind animations (glowing borders).\n2. Intelligence Layer Spec (Google AI Studio)\nGoogle AI Studio hosts our LLM backbone. We will configure Gemini 2.0 Flash as our primary reasoning engine.\n\nA. AI Studio System Instructions\nSet the following System Prompt in the AI Studio sidebar:\n\nYou are the intelligence core of the NERV Disaster Response Coordinator. Your purpose is to process highly chaotic, multimodal data (JMA alert JSON, satellite images, local tweets) and coordinate immediate evacuation and resource allocation recommendations for Japan.\n\nWhen processing, follow these rules strictly:\n1. Always parse location text (e.g., \"\346\226\260\345\256\277\345\214\272\", \"Shinjuku\") and associate it with geographic regions.\n2. For any disaster, cross-reference designated shelters (\351\201\277\351\233\243\346\211\200) based on the threat vector. DO NOT recommend a shelter flagged as unsafe for the active hazard (e.g., do not send citizens to a basement during a flood).\n3. Always output your findings and coordinated outputs in highly structured JSON formats.\n4. Keep translations accurate across Japanese (\346\227\245\346\234\254\350\252\236) and English.\nB. Schema Definition for Structured Output\nIn AI Studio, configure the model to enforce a Structured JSON Output matching this schema:\n\n{\n  \"type\": \"object\",\n  \"properties\": {\n    \"disaster_type\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"earthquake\", \"tsunami\", \"flood\", \"typhoon\", \"landslide\", \"other\"] },\n    \"intensity_max\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"description\": \"JMA Shindo scale (1 to 7)\" },\n    \"epicenter\": { \"type\": \"string\" },\n    \"affected_prefectures\": {\n      \"type\": \"array\",\n      \"items\": { \"type\": \"string\" }\n    },\n    \"immediate_hazards\": {\n      \"type\": \"array\",\n      \"items\": { \"type\": \"string\" }\n    },\n    \"agent_triage_directives\": {\n      \"type\": \"array\",\n      \"items\": { \"type\": \"string\" }\n    },\n    \"drafts\": {\n      \"type\": \"object\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"sms_alert_jp\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"maxLength\": 100 },\n        \"sms_alert_en\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"maxLength\": 100 },\n        \"social_feed_jp\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"maxLength\": 280 }\n      },\n      \"required\": [\"sms_alert_jp\", \"sms_alert_en\", \"social_feed_jp\"]\n    }\n  },\n  \"required\": [\"disaster_type\", \"intensity_max\", \"affected_prefectures\", \"immediate_hazards\", \"agent_triage_directives\", \"drafts\"]\n}\n3. Data & Integration Pipeline (Japan-Specific)\nA. The Geospatial Shelter Database\nInstead of relying on Gemini to remember shelter addresses, use a spatial search database like PostgreSQL with PostGIS or a lightweight server-side geometric library in your FastAPI backend.\n\nIngestion: Downlod GSI\342\200\231s official GeoJSON tile data of designated shelters.\nAPI Handler: Your FastAPI server exposes an endpoint: GET /api/shelters?lat=X&lng=Y&hazard=earthquake\nCalculation: It calculates distance and queries the MLIT hazard compatibility flag (earthquake_flag == true).\nResult: Returns the 5 closest safe shelters.\nB. Model Context Protocol (MCP) Integration\nConfigure the Claude/Gemini-compatible runtime to route external real-time data through two key local MCP servers:\n\n1. JMA Alert MCP Server (mcp-jma)\nExposes live seismological and meteorological telemetry directly to Gemini.\n\nSource: Integrates with the open-source https://api.p2pquake.net/v2/history feed.\nDeclared Tool: get_latest_earthquake_activity()\nReturns raw JSON detailing the exact seismic events over the last 30 minutes in Japan.\n2. X (Twitter) Alert MCP Server (mcp-twitter)\nExposes live streams from high-priority accounts like @UN_NERV.\n\nSource: Integrates with X API.\nDeclared Tool: get_emergency_broadcasts(account_handle: string)\nGets latest warnings and translated hazard maps published on X.\n4. Full Data Flow (Step-by-Step)\n[1] JMA triggers Earthquake Alert -> Caught by P2PQuake Websocket\n                                 |\n                                 v\n[2] FastAPI Server receives JSON -> Triggers Gemini 2.0 Flash (AI Studio)\n                                 |\n                                 v\n[3] Gemini uses Custom JMA MCP  -> Extracts exact coordinates, Shindo level, \n    & Twitter MCP tools            and real-time field reports from NERV\n                                 |\n                                 v\n[4] FastAPI queries database    -> Finds 5 nearest safe shelters utilizing GSI data\n                                 |\n                                 v\n[5] Server-Sent Events (SSE)    -> Streams structured updates to Google Stitch UI\n                                 |\n                                 v\n[6] React Frontend (NERV Theme) -> Highlights epicenters, renders safety routes, \n                                   and updates agent status logs instantly\n5. Next Steps for Implementation\nGenerate Frontend: Open Google Stitch, drop in the prompt from Section 1, tweak the infinite canvas, and export the React + Tailwind project files.\nConfigure AI Studio: Set up your Google AI Studio account, paste the system instructions, configure Gemini 2.0 Flash, and grab your free API Key.\nWrite Backend: Build your FastAPI app, connect it to the open-source JMA APIs, write your spatial routing functions using GSI datasets, and route everything via SSE (Server-Sent Events) to feed the beautiful Stitch UI.\n"
    items {
      text: "Build me an app with screens that look like this. You can hotlink images from the HTML\n\nThis architecture specification bridges the gap between design (Google Stitch) and intelligence (Google AI Studio) to build a state-of-the-art, highly localized Japan Disaster Response Command Center.\n\nSystem Blueprint\nOur system splits responsibilities into two optimized environments:\n\n  +-----------------------------------------------------------------+\n  |                    FRONTEND (Google Stitch)                     |\n  |                                                                 |\n  |  +--------------------+  +------------------+  +-------------+  |\n  |  |  NERV Dark Dashboard |  | Interactive Map  |  | Agent Feed  |  |\n  |  +--------------------+  +------------------+  +-------------+  |\n  +--------------------------------+--------------------------------+\n                                   | REST / SSE (Server-Sent Events)\n                                   v\n  +-----------------------------------------------------------------+\n  |                    BACKEND (FastAPI / Node)                     |\n  |                                                                 |\n  |  +--------------------+  +------------------+  +-------------+  |\n  |  | Spatial Math Engine|  | MCP Gateway      |  | Local APIs  |  |\n  |  | (Deterministic)    |  | (Twitter/JMA)    |  | (P2PQuake)  |  |\n  |  +--------------------+  +------------------+  +-------------+  |\n  +--------------------------------+--------------------------------+\n                                   | JSON / Function Calling\n                                   v\n  +-----------------------------------------------------------------+\n  |                  INTELLIGENCE (Google AI Studio)                |\n  |                                                                 |\n  |            Gemini 2.0 Flash (Multimodal & Agent Control)        |\n  +-----------------------------------------------------------------+\n1. UI Engineering Spec (Google Stitch)\nGoogle Stitch is our rapid UI prototyping engine. It will generate our high-fidelity frontend (React + Tailwind CSS) styled in a dark-theme, high-visibility layout inspired by Gehirn\'s NERV app.\n\nA. Stitch Prompt (Copy-Paste to Google Stitch Canvas)\nPaste this text prompt into your Stitch visual canvas workspace to generate the layout:\n\nCreate a high-fidelity React dashboard using Tailwind CSS. \nThe theme must be inspired by Special Agency NERV Disaster Prevention App:\n- Background: Pitch black (#050505) and dark charcoal (#121212)\n- Accents: Neon Orange (#FF6600) for warnings, Neon Purple (#9D00FF) for critical alerts, and Toxic green (#00FF66) for stable systems.\n- Font: Monospaced, tech-operational feel.\n\nLayout Requirements:\n1. Header: Shows \"NERV GEOSPATIAL COMMAND CENTER\" in bold orange, with a ticking clock, location selector (Default: Tokyo), and a glowing green \"SYSTEM ONLINE\" indicator.\n2. Center-Left (Live Map Container): A map window styled with dark vectors (to be populated by Google Maps / GSI Tiles) showing local escape routes, evacuation sites, and seismic epicenters.\n3. Center-Right (Real-time Intel Stream): A scrolling log of incoming news feeds and automated tweets with raw text and images.\n4. Bottom-Left (Shelter & Resource Locator): A grid panel showing the closest designated shelters (\346\214\207\345\256\232\351\201\277\351\233\243\346\211\200) from a user\'s geolocation, complete with distance indicators and hazard compatibility badges (Earthquake, Tsunami, Flood safety flags).\n5. Bottom-Right (Gemini 2.0 Flash Multi-Agent Output): A split panel showing:\n   - \"Triage Engine\" status log.\n   - \"Resource Coordinator\" recommended actions.\n   - \"Public Broadcaster\" dynamic multi-lingual alerts ready to copy.\n6. Controls: Simulated controls to upload a satellite photo or trigger a mock seismic event (e.g., Magnitude 7.2 earthquake off Tokyo Bay).\nB. Generated Component Architecture (Exported from Stitch)\nDashboardLayout.tsx: Grid wrapper managing the 3-column layout.\nMapCanvas.tsx: Hosts the dark-styled interactive Google Maps API.\nShelterGrid.tsx: Lists closest locations filtered by distance and status.\nAgentResponseCard.tsx: Standard component handling streaming output using Tailwind animations (glowing borders).\n2. Intelligence Layer Spec (Google AI Studio)\nGoogle AI Studio hosts our LLM backbone. We will configure Gemini 2.0 Flash as our primary reasoning engine.\n\nA. AI Studio System Instructions\nSet the following System Prompt in the AI Studio sidebar:\n\nYou are the intelligence core of the NERV Disaster Response Coordinator. Your purpose is to process highly chaotic, multimodal data (JMA alert JSON, satellite images, local tweets) and coordinate immediate evacuation and resource allocation recommendations for Japan.\n\nWhen processing, follow these rules strictly:\n1. Always parse location text (e.g., \"\346\226\260\345\256\277\345\214\272\", \"Shinjuku\") and associate it with geographic regions.\n2. For any disaster, cross-reference designated shelters (\351\201\277\351\233\243\346\211\200) based on the threat vector. DO NOT recommend a shelter flagged as unsafe for the active hazard (e.g., do not send citizens to a basement during a flood).\n3. Always output your findings and coordinated outputs in highly structured JSON formats.\n4. Keep translations accurate across Japanese (\346\227\245\346\234\254\350\252\236) and English.\nB. Schema Definition for Structured Output\nIn AI Studio, configure the model to enforce a Structured JSON Output matching this schema:\n\n{\n  \"type\": \"object\",\n  \"properties\": {\n    \"disaster_type\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"earthquake\", \"tsunami\", \"flood\", \"typhoon\", \"landslide\", \"other\"] },\n    \"intensity_max\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"description\": \"JMA Shindo scale (1 to 7)\" },\n    \"epicenter\": { \"type\": \"string\" },\n    \"affected_prefectures\": {\n      \"type\": \"array\",\n      \"items\": { \"type\": \"string\" }\n    },\n    \"immediate_hazards\": {\n      \"type\": \"array\",\n      \"items\": { \"type\": \"string\" }\n    },\n    \"agent_triage_directives\": {\n      \"type\": \"array\",\n      \"items\": { \"type\": \"string\" }\n    },\n    \"drafts\": {\n      \"type\": \"object\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"sms_alert_jp\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"maxLength\": 100 },\n        \"sms_alert_en\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"maxLength\": 100 },\n        \"social_feed_jp\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"maxLength\": 280 }\n      },\n      \"required\": [\"sms_alert_jp\", \"sms_alert_en\", \"social_feed_jp\"]\n    }\n  },\n  \"required\": [\"disaster_type\", \"intensity_max\", \"affected_prefectures\", \"immediate_hazards\", \"agent_triage_directives\", \"drafts\"]\n}\n3. Data & Integration Pipeline (Japan-Specific)\nA. The Geospatial Shelter Database\nInstead of relying on Gemini to remember shelter addresses, use a spatial search database like PostgreSQL with PostGIS or a lightweight server-side geometric library in your FastAPI backend.\n\nIngestion: Downlod GSI\342\200\231s official GeoJSON tile data of designated shelters.\nAPI Handler: Your FastAPI server exposes an endpoint: GET /api/shelters?lat=X&lng=Y&hazard=earthquake\nCalculation: It calculates distance and queries the MLIT hazard compatibility flag (earthquake_flag == true).\nResult: Returns the 5 closest safe shelters.\nB. Model Context Protocol (MCP) Integration\nConfigure the Claude/Gemini-compatible runtime to route external real-time data through two key local MCP servers:\n\n1. JMA Alert MCP Server (mcp-jma)\nExposes live seismological and meteorological telemetry directly to Gemini.\n\nSource: Integrates with the open-source https://api.p2pquake.net/v2/history feed.\nDeclared Tool: get_latest_earthquake_activity()\nReturns raw JSON detailing the exact seismic events over the last 30 minutes in Japan.\n2. X (Twitter) Alert MCP Server (mcp-twitter)\nExposes live streams from high-priority accounts like @UN_NERV.\n\nSource: Integrates with X API.\nDeclared Tool: get_emergency_broadcasts(account_handle: string)\nGets latest warnings and translated hazard maps published on X.\n4. Full Data Flow (Step-by-Step)\n[1] JMA triggers Earthquake Alert -> Caught by P2PQuake Websocket\n                                 |\n                                 v\n[2] FastAPI Server receives JSON -> Triggers Gemini 2.0 Flash (AI Studio)\n                                 |\n                                 v\n[3] Gemini uses Custom JMA MCP  -> Extracts exact coordinates, Shindo level, \n    & Twitter MCP tools            and real-time field reports from NERV\n                                 |\n                                 v\n[4] FastAPI queries database    -> Finds 5 nearest safe shelters utilizing GSI data\n                                 |\n                                 v\n[5] Server-Sent Events (SSE)    -> Streams structured updates to Google Stitch UI\n                                 |\n                                 v\n[6] React Frontend (NERV Theme) -> Highlights epicenters, renders safety routes, \n                                   and updates agent status logs instantly\n5. Next Steps for Implementation\nGenerate Frontend: Open Google Stitch, drop in the prompt from Section 1, tweak the infinite canvas, and export the React + Tailwind project files.\nConfigure AI Studio: Set up your Google AI Studio account, paste the system instructions, configure Gemini 2.0 Flash, and grab your free API Key.\nWrite Backend: Build your FastAPI app, connect it to the open-source JMA APIs, write your spatial routing functions using GSI datasets, and route everything via SSE (Server-Sent Events) to feed the beautiful Stitch UI.\n"
