  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Clarifying User Needs**\n\nI\'m now diving into the user requirements, taking a look at that mock image. It\'s helping me understand the application\'s core functions, specifically the `NERV GEOSPATIAL COMMAND CENTER` title and the prominent `LIVE_STREAM` tag that\'s flashing. I also see header info, all of which will help me design and implement the app. I am ready to design the app and implement server.ts and the front end.\n\n\n**Defining App Interface Elements**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the UI components. I\'ve got the time display, location selector, and operational status indicator nailed down. The side navigation will have several modes: Geospatial, Intel Stream, Resource Locator, Multi-Agent AI, and Simulation. Now I\'m working on the central tactical map view and debating between a dark-styled Google Map, a custom canvas, or a standard map API. Custom vector drawing and interactive elements are a must!\n\n\n**Designing Interactive Map**\n\nI\'ve decided on a highly detailed, interactive vector map as the central UI element. It\'ll be a dark, custom map - either Leaflet with dark tiles, or a styled Google Map, or a rich vector canvas. It must have clickable elements, glowing targets, escape routes, seismic animations, and satellite overlays. The goal is to build a map that looks exactly like the NERV command center display.\n\n\n**Analyzing Intel Stream Data**\n\nI\'m now deep-diving into the `INTEL_STREAM` data feed and the `TRIAGE_ENGINE`\'s readouts. The goal is to capture the application\'s unique features, such as the `NERV` and `JMA` alerts and `AGENT_GEMINI` actions. The focus is now on the dynamic interplay of real-time data, analytical processing, and suggested actions displayed on the right pane of the NERV display.\n\n\n**Prioritizing UI Elements**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on high-priority UI elements. Specifically, the \"Public Broadcaster\" with its bilingual evacuation alerts and the prominent orange transmit button. I\'m building out the \"Shelter & Resource Locator\" with shelter details, including distances and hazard badges. Finally, I\'m integrating the simulation controls for earthquake and satellite image uploads, and the bottom status bar for uptime.\n\n\n**Defining Backend Tasks**\n\nI\'m now outlining the backend API\'s core responsibilities. The server will deliver static assets and handle Vite middleware, as expected. I\'ll need to create a real-time JMA Alert telemetry route, perhaps using a mock generator initially, and integrating with the p2pquake API. There are two MCP servers to build. I\'m focusing on GET /api/earthquakes endpoint using p2pquake.net for real earthquake data.\n\n\n**Implementing Real-time Data Feeds**\n\nI\'ve just added real p2pquake integration, which feels great! I\'m now building several API endpoints: one for shelters with distance filtering, one for image triage with Gemini, and a stream for real-time updates. The SSE stream will be for telemetry, triggered by mock earthquakes or real alerts. I\'m checking that all the necessary packages are installed, including `@google/genai` and `lucide-react`. I am very excited by the ability to connect to real-time data sources.\n\n\n**Designing Custom Vector Map**\n\nI\'ve decided to create an SVG-based custom vector map, which is perfect for a dark, high-stakes dashboard. I\'m focusing on a detailed Tokyo Bay map with gridlines, coordinate readouts, and landmass contours. I\'m excited to create dynamic epicenter markers with pulsating shockwaves, glowing safe shelters, and evacuation routes. I\'m also ensuring the map supports simulation mode. I\'ve now installed `@motion/react` for animations.\n\n\n**Integrating Satellite Thermal Data**\n\nI\'m now implementing the satellite thermal scan overlay for the Tokyo map, ensuring responsive zoom and pan controls. I\'ll provide a high-fidelity SVG map and integrate real-time JMA alerts. I\'m double-checking the shelter database requirements, preparing to define a rich dataset of Tokyo shelters with hazard flags. This will involve loading the data in `server.ts` and computing spatial distances.\n\n\n**Defining AI Triage Schema**\n\nI\'m now drafting the structured output schema for the AI triage system. I\'m focusing on defining properties like disaster type, intensity, epicenter, affected prefectures, immediate hazards, directives, and drafts for multilingual SMS and social media alerts, all using JSON. The schema\'s structure is coming together!\n\n\n\n**Defining AI Triage Schema**\n\nI\'m now drafting the structured output schema for the AI triage system. I\'m focusing on defining properties like disaster type, intensity, epicenter, affected prefectures, immediate hazards, directives, and drafts for multilingual SMS and social media alerts, all using JSON. The schema\'s structure is coming together!\n\n\\n\\n\n\nI\'m now figuring out the direct conversion of the JSON schema to TypeScript types, specifically for `@google/genai`\'s `responseSchema`. The `gemini-api` skill makes heavy use of it using `Type.OBJECT`, `Type.STRING`, and etc. I need to make sure I am writing correct Type Definitions. This conversion step is crucial for accurate data retrieval from Gemini.\n\n\n**Implementing Server-Side API**\n\nI\'m now implementing the backend API and server components, starting with static file serving and Vite middleware. I\'m focusing on the `/api/shelters` endpoint, which will calculate distances to Tokyo shelters and filter them based on hazard flags. Next, the `/api/triage` endpoint, integrating with Gemini 3.5 Flash for image and text processing to return the structured JSON results, is on deck.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create the backend `server.ts` file, implementing the NERV Disaster Response spatial engine, JMA / P2PQuake integration, a local designated shelter database, and Gemini 3.5 Flash triage analyzer with structured output."
