  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Prioritizing Intuitive Design**\n\nI\'m focusing on map intuitiveness now. I\'m starting by analyzing the elements that make a map easy to understand. The goal is a visually clear, easily navigable interface before any name integration. Dark and light modes are in the plan, as well.\n\n\n**Defining Key Map Elements**\n\nI\'ve been thinking about the critical components for an effective map. I\'m prioritizing color schemes for land and water, beautiful coastal outlines, and labeling of key bays and peninsulas to aid in quick identification. I also want to integrate crucial landmarks and icons to provide immediate user context and interactivity through hover triggers on shelters and landmarks, and now, even dynamic earthquake epicenter simulations triggered by clicks. I\'m really getting excited about the potential of a fully interactive and intuitive map!\n\n\n**Implementing Click Functionality**\n\nI\'m now integrating click interactivity. I\'ve defined projection and deprojection functions in `TacticalMap.tsx` to handle coordinate transformations between latitude/longitude and SVG viewBox coordinates. This enables me to map user clicks to geographic locations. Clicking now triggers a custom epicenter simulation when in the simulation tab. This adds a valuable interactive dimension to the map.\n\n\n**Adding Landmark Coordinates**\n\nI\'m now redesigning `TacticalMap.tsx` with landmark integration. I\'m mapping landmarks using coordinates and projections. I\'ve calculated and placed Mount Fuji at `x = 40, y = 540` and labeled it. Now, I\'m integrating Tokyo Tower at `x = 343, y = 332` and Tokyo Skytree at `x = 495, y = 189`. I am excited to see these landmark coordinates come to life on the map.\n\n\n**Calculating Landmark Coordinates**\n\nI\'m now calculating more landmark coordinates for the map. I\'ve computed coordinates for Haneda Airport, Odaiba, and Shibaura, and determined how to represent the Rainbow Bridge connecting them, which will involve drawing a line from Shibaura to Odaiba. The math is coming together nicely!\n\n\n**Mapping Tokyo Bay Aqualine**\n\nI\'m now integrating the Tokyo Bay Aqualine into the map, using calculated coordinates for Kawasaki and Kisarazu shores, drawing a dashed line between them, and adding a circle labeled \"Umi-hotaru PA\" in the middle to complete the look. I have adjusted the landmass coordinates to match the Aqualine\'s path, starting from the bottom-left of the SVG at (0,600).\n\n\n**Defining Landmass Topology**\n\nI\'m now focusing on defining the landmass polygon, crucial for the map\'s overall structure. I\'m starting from the bottom-left corner and defining the shape of the land. I\'m focusing on defining the coast line. I\'m calculating coordinate points for Yokohama, Kawasaki, Haneda, Shinagawa, and I\'m refining my strategy, which will involve describing the entire top, west, and east of the canvas.\n\n\n**Finalizing Landmass Definition**\n\nI\'ve finalized the landmass polygon, creating a visually clear separation between land and water. The polygon describes the coastline precisely. I\'m excited; it now covers the top section and leaves the bottom portion for water. I\'ve chosen colors for the land and water in both light and dark modes and defined a coastline stroke.\n\n\n**Defining Color Schemes**\n\nI\'ve defined the color schemes for both light and dark modes! In light mode, the water will be a soft ice blue (`#e3f2fd`), land a warm off-white sand (`#fcfbfa`), and the coastline a soft light steel blue (`#b0c4de` or `#c3cbd6`). I\'m also planning to draw rivers on top of the land. In dark mode, I will set those values to different values for full light/dark mode support. I will be drawing rivers. I will start by the Sumida, Arakawa, and Edo rivers, which will look fantastic!\n\n\n\n**Integrating River Placement**\n\nI\'m now integrating rivers like the Sumida, Arakawa, and Edo, and also some labels, such as \"TOKYO BAY\", at `x = 500, y = 500`, and \"BOSO PENINSULA\", at `x = 710, y = 560`. I\'m starting to think about dynamic sonar scan lines for active alerts and how a user can trigger a simulation directly from the map, using relative click coordinates. I plan to add an `onMapClick` prop to `TacticalMap` to link clicks to simulations. This will allow for intuitive earthquake triggering directly on the map.\n\n\n**Enhancing Interactive Features**\n\nI\'m now integrating the visual enhancements and theming into `TacticalMap.tsx`. I\'m focusing on incorporating a \"TACTICAL SANDBOX MODE\" overlay and on allowing earthquake simulations triggered by a map click. I\'m adding `onMapClick` to receive coordinate data. I\'m now adding a toggle to enable simulation on click. I have fully written the code for the light/dark theme support and the interactivity, which makes the map even more dynamic.\n\n\n**Incorporating Detailed Icons**\n\nI\'m now integrating Lucide icons and designing custom SVG components. I\'ve added `MapPin`, `AlertOctagon`, and `Info` from Lucide. I\'ve crafted a detailed SVG for the Tokyo Tower with blinking elements and another for the Tokyo Skytree, now with the correct styling and animations. I will start testing these components for correctness and ease of integration into the SVG.\n\n\n**Refining Visual Details**\n\nI\'m now focusing on refining the visual details. I\'ve enhanced the Tokyo Tower and Tokyo Skytree SVGs with blinking elements and proper styling. The styling of the components is more precise, with styling and animations. I\'m testing the components for integration and correctness within the SVG. I\'ve drawn a dashed line and added some visual details for the Rainbow Bridge between Shibaura and Odaiba.\n\n\n**Adding Airport Runways**\n\nI\'ve added the Haneda Airport runways near coordinates `x = 220, y = 510`, complete with runway markers. I am excited about the visual addition this will add to the map.\n\n\n\n**Implementing Click Interactivity**\n\nI\'m now integrating general map click handling via `handleSvgClick`, enabling interactive triggers. I\'ve successfully implemented click-to-trigger earthquake simulations, now detecting clicks within the SVG element and calculating relative coordinates. I have integrated checks to see if users are selecting a shelter. Click coordinates are mapped to lat/lng and passed to `onMapClick`, allowing dynamic simulations. Now, I have added the capability to toggle simulations with the click of a button.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will now replace the entire contents of `/src/components/TacticalMap.tsx` with a highly refined, intuitive, interactive, and beautiful tactical map that supports light/dark themes, includes major landmarks (Tokyo Tower, Tokyo Skytree, Haneda Airport, Rainbow Bridge, Aqualine), shows labels, and allows users to click anywhere on the map to trigger a simulated disaster."
